title: U.S. Rests Its Case in the Elizabeth Holmes Trial
content: Defense lawyers are expected to argue that the founder of Theranos, the blood-testing start-up, failed but did not commit fraud.

title: A Hoffa Ally, Then a Foe, and Soon the Teamsters President
content: Sean O’Brien scored a decisive victory among union members after criticizing the current leadership as too timid in UPS talks and Amazon organizing.

title: Can a Machine Learn Morality?
content: Researchers at a Seattle A.I. lab say they have built a system that makes ethical judgments. But its judgments can be as confusing as those of humans.

title: Leased Your Car? You Could Get a Great Deal on It.
content: People who leased their cars before the pandemic can probably buy their vehicles at the end of the lease for much less than the going market price.

title: How to Beat Retirement’s Nemesis: Inflation
content: With prices rising at their fastest rate in decades, people in retirement or approaching it should take extra care to protect their savings.

title: He Helped Build Tesla. Now He’s Gunning for It.
content: Peter Rawlinson engineered the Tesla Model S. His new Lucid Air sedan is a direct challenge to Tesla’s dominance.

more_info.byline: By Niraj Chokshi and Jack Ewing

title: Buy Stocks to Prosper. Buy Bonds to Sleep at Night.
content: Do what it takes to stay invested in the stock market, our columnist says. Government bonds may help, even if they look unappealing now.

title: Judge Tries to Block New York Times’s Coverage of Project Veritas
content: The state court order, which The Times said it would immediately oppose, raised concerns from First Amendment advocates.

title: Google questions if the new Justice Department antitrust boss can be impartial.
content: Jonathan Kanter, who was confirmed by the Senate earlier this week as the assistant attorney general for antitrust, has been a longtime behind-the-scenes player in building arguments against tech giants.

title: With ‘New York Ninja,’ Lights, Camera and, Finally, Action
content: The 1984 kung fu film was shot, but it wasn’t completed. Now, with a new director and newly recorded dialogue, the film sees the light of day.

title: BuzzFeed plans to start publicly trading in early December.
content: The company still loses money, but its revenue rose 20 percent in the third quarter. Investors who want to own a piece can do so around Dec. 6.

title: Roosevelt Statue to Head to Presidential Library in North Dakota
content: The American Museum of Natural History’s memorial, which has stirred objections as a symbol of colonialism and racism, is planned for display at a library opening in 2026.

title: Bettina Plevan, Litigator Who Shattered Glass Ceilings, Dies at 75
content: After her own meteoric rise to partner at Proskauer Rose, where she handled sexual harassment cases, she helped other women advance in the legal profession.

title: House Narrowly Passes Biden’s Social Safety Net and Climate Bill
content: The vote was months in the making for the roughly $2 trillion measure, one of the most consequential bills in decades. Now it faces a difficult path in the Senate.

more_info.byline: By Emily Cochrane and Jonathan Weisman

title: One meme stock lawsuit against Robinhood is dismissed, but others loom.
content: The suit was part of a proposed three-part class action suit against Robinhood and others over their roles in January’s GameStop trading frenzy.

title: Ford Has a D.I.Y. Plan for Computer Chips
content: The carmaker is betting it can make its own semiconductors and avoid another supply crunch.

more_info.byline: By Andrew Ross Sorkin, Jason Karaian, Sarah Kessler, Stephen Gandel, Michael J. de la Merced, Lauren Hirsch and Ephrat Livni

title: Japan approves a $490 billion economic stimulus package as the pandemic’s effects linger.
content: The move, announced on Friday, is an attempt by the country’s newish prime minister to revive an economy battered by Covid restrictions and a supply chain crunch.

title: In Rare Show of Weakness, Modi Bows to India’s Farmers
content: A bungled response to Covid and a struggling economy have hurt his party’s standing, leaving it vulnerable to a well-organized protest movement.

more_info.byline: By Emily Schmall, Karan Deep Singh and Sameer Yasir

title: Cryptocurrency group loses bid for copy of U.S. Constitution.
content: ConstitutionDAO, a “decentralized autonomous organization,” had raised more than $40 million to bid for the artifact.

title: The company that produced ‘Parasite’ has bought Endeavor’s scripted content arm.
content: Endeavor was forced to reduce its ownership stake in its scripted content business as a result of a settlement with the Writers Guild of America.

title: Critic of Teamsters leader claims victory in race to succeed him.
content: Sean O’Brien said he would be more aggressive than the incumbent, James P. Hoffa, in his approach to Amazon and UPS.

title: How Elizabeth Holmes Soured the Media on Silicon Valley
content: Testimony in the fraud trial of Ms. Holmes, the founder of the blood testing start-up Theranos, shows how much coverage of the tech industry has changed over the years.

more_info.byline: By Erin Griffith and Erin Woo

title: Overlooked No More: Ruth Polsky, Who Shaped New York’s Music Scene
content: She booked concerts at influential nightclubs in the 1980s, bringing exposure to up-and-coming artists like the Smiths and New Order.

title: The Crypto Company Behind the Renaming of the Los Angeles Staples Center
content: What’s Crypto.com, which is paying $700 million for the naming rights to the sports venue?

title: State attorneys general open an inquiry into Instagram’s impact on teens.
content: The states were examining whether the actions of Facebook, now called Meta, violated state consumer protection laws and put the public at risk.

more_info.byline: By Cecilia Kang and Mike Isaac

title: Tax Deduction That Benefits the Rich Divides Democrats Before Vote
content: House Democrats are poised to lift a cap on the state and local tax deduction, a gift to wealthy homeowners in some blue states.

more_info.byline: By Alan Rappeport and Patrick McGeehan

title: Ford Moves to Ensure Supply of Chips and Guide Their Design
content: The automaker will team with GlobalFoundries on producing and developing semiconductors, crucial parts that have been in short supply.

more_info.byline: By Neal E. Boudette and Don Clark

title: CVS will close 900 stores as it looks beyond traditional pharmacies.
content: The company said the closures, which will affect about 9 percent of its stores in the next three years, were part of a shift in focus.

title: I Spoke to C.E.O.s About the Future of Work
content: Big companies are struggling with how, when and even if they will bring employees back to the office.

title: Oprah Winfrey and Reese Witherspoon join in a private equity takeover of Spanx.
content: It’s the latest investment deal for the celebrities, whose financial backing is valued as a stamp of approval for consumer brands.

title: Macy’s raises its full-year outlook after strong third-quarter sales.
content: The retailer said its sales for the three months that ended on Oct. 30 were $5.4 billion, and it posted a net profit of $239 million.

title: Investors Are Charging Up Electric-Vehicle Stocks
content: Shares in Lucid Motors and Rivian are soaring. Can that last?

title: A Hot Rod Before Its Time: Ford’s Model A, With a Boost
content: This car was built almost exclusively with 1930s mechanical components, but it has been driven as fast as 70 m.p.h.
